description.narrative: (Angola): Health For All (HFA) will support activities to improve malaria surveillance, monitoring, and evaluation; health systems strengthening; malaria prevention; case management; and social behavior communication (SBC). HFA will strengthen monthly malaria surveillance data reporting and National Malaria Control Program (NMCP) capacity through the roll-out of the District Health Information System 2. HFA will monitor the distribution of bed nets, will support harmonization of malaria in pregnancy activities between provincial malaria and reproductive health supervisors, and will support efforts to increase uptake of intermittent preventive treatment in pregnancy. HFA will support the 2022 mass campaign through planning and oversight while building NMCP's capacity to conduct national campaigns.HFA will implement SBC activities to increase antenatal care uptake, improve communication between healthcare workers and caretakers and carry-out a Therapeutic Efficacy Survey to measure for signs of antimalarial resistance. HFA implements family planning and reproductive health (FP/RH) activities in Luanda and Huambo provinces. HFA will disseminate existing strategies, policies and guidelines on RH at the provincial and municipal levels; strengthen the capacity of provincial health departments to expand the FP service model into additional health units; develop and spread messages on healthy timing and spacing of pregnancy (HTSP) including gender-based violence; increase the use and transfer of the Health Network Quality Improvement System monitoring tool at the provincial and municipal level; expand demand of long-acting methods; continue the Digital Campaign on RH for youth; and support the MoH in developing a costed-implementation plan that will describe how much the national FP efforts will cost. This is a roadmap that will help the GRA achieve its FP goals effectively.

Objectives for Angola: The project aims for a 40 percent reduction in malaria through nationwide insecticide-treated net distribution campaigns and improvement of the quality of clinical malaria services; 90 percent of people living with HIV placed on treatment in Luanda with the establishment of a sustainable model for quality HIV/AIDS services; 30 percent to 53 percent increase in national use of contraceptives as a result of high-level technical assistance in family planning/sexual and reproductive health; Technicians’ capacity to develop and monitor health budgets at the provincial and municipal level to develop and monitor health budgets will be strengthened.
